## EPIC-001 — Structured EPIC Markdown Parser & Serializer

**Phase:** 1
**Priority:** P0 — Foundation
**Estimated Effort:** 2 days
Roles: engineer, qa
### Description

The current `MarkdownPreview.tsx` is a naive line-by-line renderer that doesn't understand the EPIC plan schema. `PlanEditorTab.tsx` is a raw `<textarea>` with no structured awareness. This EPIC builds the parsing layer that every other feature depends on: a TypeScript module in `src/lib/epic-parser.ts` that converts plan markdown into a typed AST (`EpicDocument`) and back again. The parser must handle all elements present in real plan files — frontmatter fields (`**Phase:** 1`, `**Owner:** engineer`), `- [ ]` / `- [x]` checklists for DoD/Tasks/AC, task IDs (`**T-005.1**`), nested code blocks inside tasks, `depends_on: [...]` YAML blocks, and horizontal rules between EPICs. The serializer must round-trip perfectly: `serialize(parse(original)) === original` for every existing `.md` file in the repo.

### Context

Currently used markdown files to parse against:
- `PLAN.md` (8 EPICs, 23 tasks, mixed checkbox states, one `depends_on`)
- `PLAN-GROWTH.md` (this file — 3 EPICs with code blocks in tasks)
- `refactor-skills-ui.md` (3 EPICs, different heading styles using `####`)
- Plan templates in `src/lib/plan-templates.ts` (3 templates with varying structures)

Key pattern variations to handle:
- `### EPIC-001` vs `## EPIC-001` heading levels
- `#### Objective` vs `### Description` section headers
- `Roles: engineer, qa` inline metadata vs `**Owner:** engineer` bold-key format
- `depends_on: []` inline vs ` ```yaml\ndepends_on: [...]\n``` ` fenced blocks
- Task descriptions with nested markdown (code blocks, sub-lists, bold text)

### Definition of Done

- [ ] `parseEpicMarkdown(md: string): EpicDocument` parses all plan files in the repo without errors
- [ ] `serializeEpicMarkdown(doc: EpicDocument): string` produces output identical to the input for every test file
- [ ] Parser extracts: plan title, goal, config block, and per-EPIC: ref, title, frontmatter, description, DoD[], tasks[], AC[], depends_on[]
- [ ] Checkbox items (`- [ ]` / `- [x]`) correctly map to `{ text, checked }` and back
- [ ] Task IDs (`**T-XXX.N**`) parsed into `{ id, title, description, completed }` objects
- [ ] Code blocks within task descriptions preserved verbatim through round-trip
- [ ] `depends_on` extracted whether inline or in fenced YAML block
- [ ] Vitest test suite with 100% coverage of parser and serializer

